The menu of a fat kid: He doesn't eat breakfast and he eats sausage for dinner
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 are overweight, with 9 percent of all students and 5 percent of all children being overweight.
Recent surveys have shown that obese children are mostly from families with unhealthy lifestyles.
This shows once again how important the environment in which a person grows up and the examples around him are for healthy development.
On the tables of obese children, sausages are up to half as often on the table as in families where normal-weight children live.
More than 19 percent of the overweight children had potatoes for dinner the day before the "Obesity is no accident" education campaign.
In families with fat children, sports are not a favorite activity, but they are also a concern for the majority of students today - only 15 percent said their parents have time for active exercise at least once a week.
Survey of 900 children
The survey was conducted at the end of the school year last year and involved almost 900 children from primary schools across the Czech Republic.
This was the second year of the 'Obesity is no coincidence' campaign, supported by the General Health Fund and Unilever.
So far, more than 12 thousand pupils from 4th and 8th grades have taken part in the project.
Unhealthy diet and lack of family activity are key factors that are responsible for the alarming increase in the number of overweight or even obese children.
"For example, only half of the children surveyed reported eating breakfast, lunch, and dinner five times a day - a key requirement for a healthy diet", says one of the survey results.
No breakfast and no sausage for dinner
Experts point out that even relative small things, such as the family's regular breakfast time, are important for a child's healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23 percent of the families eat breakfast.
And in most families, everyone eats breakfast on their own.
The worst was the finding that one in ten families does not have breakfast at all.
Breakfast is considered the cornerstone of a healthy daily diet.
The survey showed, among other things, that in families with overweight children, unhealthy potatoes are much more common.
And almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet lemonade every day (70 percent)
While more than 40 percent of children surveyed do exercise, less than half of their parents do - just 15 percent.
Make your own menu
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to draw up their own meal plans based on their appetite and opinion.
"What Czech children between 12 and 15 years old prefer in terms of nutrition is far from the ideal of a healthy diet.
Among her favorite foods were many meals of flour, meat, and, of course, sweets.
"The high popularity of sweet lemonades is particularly alarming", the final report of this survey stresses.
At lunch, the main course, doughnuts were just ahead of poultry.
The children hardly liked legumes at all, and the popularity of fish and vegetable dishes for lunch was very low.
Return to Health
But at the same time, the survey also showed that children are willing to change their eating habits when they are given the right information.
"The control group of respondents who completed the questionnaire following the completion of the 'Obesity is not a coincidence' lecture saw a significant shift in preferences towards healthy eating principles in many cases", the results of the project stated.
This was the case for a moment, for example, in the sweet limos, where many children began to prefer ordinary water.
The children also crossed the questionnaire with much more poultry or fish as the main dish of the day and were willing to eat fewer buns or sweet foods.
Professionals say a stylist must be a good psychologist
In the introductory article on how to learn stylists, I had a little bit of a complaint that this was a little too much material for the start.
I had no idea what was coming.
Lectures by three industry professionals, the dress of problematic figures and a seminar on how "on the spot" works.
It's supposed to get worse.
The closer the examination gets, the more information and practical tasks we have to face.
But even if the course takes place every Saturday and Sunday, it's still full.
This time we debated with Director Alena (not a single man takes part in the course) how to attract a woman who does not have an ideal figure.
And most of us are.
Some have a very short neck, others a very young figure with no proper curves, and still others are sloppy.
It is the stylist's job to visually cover up wide shoulders, extend the neck, or create the necessary curves.
We also got tips on how to dress a woman like Jennifer Lopez -- with big boobs, wide hips and a thin waist -- pretty and figurative without being too provocative.
For example, if the difference between waist and hips is so great that the skirt or pants really don't fit, you should at least get a custom cut.
I'm sure you won't regret it, because clothes that fit well are simply priceless.
In such a custom-made skirt, you feel much better than in a stick that always slides up and down, falls down the waist, etc.
Young figures, in turn, can afford to wear clothing with wrinkles, underpants, applications, embroidery or raffles.
With all this information and all these types of characters, I'm glad I have a whole week to get it all in my head.
And yet I'm afraid that given the homework that's on it, it's almost impossible to do.
Each of the students was assigned a celebrity to design appropriate outfits - day and evening clothes.
We should take into account the current appearance, the fashion style of the corresponding star and its figure type.
I'm supposed to be "dressing" Miranda Kerr, who you may know from the Victoria's Secret campaign.
I'm cheering inside, because it's much better for me personally than, say, Britney Spears or Christina Aguilera, who has gained a hundred pounds lately (well, that's a bit exaggerated), or even the young Selena Gomez.
The clothes are to be cut out of magazines or searched the Internet, printed, and then graphically edited.
The mood board, as the whole result is called, is then to express our very personal style and our relationship to graphic design.
It's very important to think about the graphic side of styling.
The stylist not only attracts the models physically, but also designs the so-called product page in the journals (according to specifications, e.g. trend handbags, coats, etc.).
This is what Mario Kameník, a stylist and designer, told us.
But not until Sunday.
That means a stylist needs to have a good overview.
The Saturday lecture, which included information on the types of figures, was immediately spiced by three industry visitors:
by the stylist Jan Pokorný, fashion designer Jakub Polanka and fashion photographer Ben Renč.
Jacob reminded us that fashion is an illusion and that a stylist should be able to take advantage of this.
And a skilled stylist can work with a single piece of clothing in a whole different way.
The magic word is "variability".
So you can wear a trenchcoat, like you usually do, over jeans, like a T-shirt or coat, but you can also wear it on the naked body, put your heel shoes on it and wear it as a dress.
Just squint the sleeve or collar up and the whole look looks different.
"Play with it", he stressed.
But the advice that struck me most was: "First you must know the rules perfectly".
"Only then can you hurt them", Jacob said.
I finally understand why we have to pack all these lessons, what you can combine with what, and why, even though you often see something completely different in fashion magazines.
Not to mention fashion shows.
Thanks to photographer Ben, I now know that a stylist must have prepared far more clothing than he ultimately photographs.
So for a fashion story with 10 pages, you have to be prepared to style at least 15.
And also that the clothes in the photo, combined with other accessories, sometimes look very different than they do in reality.
So all of this is what you have to look for when you design the outfit.
That image and style sometimes make up half of success, Jan Pokorný also confirmed to us.
All you need to do is look at Madonna, a not-so-brilliant singer whose image and marketing have made her a world star.
In the Czech Republic, the services of a stylist are more reserved.
Even celebrities often consider this to be money thrown out (the main thing is that bringing something that looks like me is secondary).
And if any of us are getting styled, then we should expect that he or she is likely to force us to a completely different size than he or she actually needs.
Then you just have to google to see for sure that the tabloid press is saying the celebrity has gone up or down, etc.
Jan and Mario told us on Sunday not to believe that a stylist needs to focus on fashion and then "build" the outfit.
He's got to communicate with the people he's working with, and he's got to be a skilled psychologist.
I'm not going to judge people without being insulted or agreeing with their opinions.
"If some manager orders us to look at her closet and add some pretty stuff, we can't just empty her out of the closet and say, 'Oh my God, that's terrible.'"
"You have to find at least some commendable things to recommend and contribute to", says Mario.
He also showed us in a very concrete way what a so-called "plate bag" must contain.
So, this is a bag that you can button on your waist and carry all the properties you need.
In addition to clear objects such as scissors, hair removal wipers or safety needles, it also contains utensils such as a nylon thread (which helps the stylist photograph products such as handbags or hats), special clips to rub the back of the clothing if it is too large (no needles or other staples to prevent the fabric from breaking) and, of course, sewing.
But so that we could not only listen but also try something practical, we learned how to properly glue shoes.
Even when you're taking pictures in a studio where the floor is flat, you can damage the shoe soles, let alone the outside.
We're sticking and sticking...
You can't even touch your shoes with a scissor, so you don't damage them.
So you really have to be smart.
Mario delighted me by praising my "creation" without limitations.
I'm not exactly a strong man for that skill.
All of this was just a fraction of what we heard on the second weekend continuation course.
One thing I've come to realize is that professional styling is not a child's play.
