IBM innovator enters the second century of its existence
If you wanted to find a word that would be the most accurate description of IBM's strategy, it would probably be the word "longevity".
To the general public, IBM is synonymous with technological revolution, known as a modern company, even though it's been around for a century.
The foundation for this longevity was laid by its first head, the visionary Thomas J. Watson.
He was already using the slogan that countless global problems could be easily solved if people were willing to think a little bit.
His slogan "Think!" became the trademark for the future giant's life (and at the same time the title of the company's internal magazine, which IBM began publishing in 1935).
This was also the basis of the corporate culture that Watson prepared thoroughly.
"For us at IBM, this long-term thinking is a continuous movement toward the future.
IBM survived and succeeded for a whole century because it remained true to its principles and was not afraid to change everything else around it.
This allowed us to transform technology, business and society throughout our first century.
We hope to create even more in the next hundred years", said Samuel J. Palmisano, the company's current director, on the occasion of the anniversary.
A well-thought-out system
