The trend in travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five authorised state travel agencies in the then-CSSR: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies at the time sold mainly to travel to the socialist Eastern Bloc countries, and only selected travellers were allowed to travel to the West.
And so Czech tourists traveled to the Baltic Sea (the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimean peninsula on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania on the Black Sea, and to Hungary on the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when travel to Yugoslavia was also allowed, when Yugoslavia took a pro-Western route and therefore travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of the socialist era was that even citizens of the Eastern Bloc (and thus Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the USSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he would need a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual travel would not be possible.
Even then travel agencies offered to travel west, but then you had to buy giant snakes or sleep in a sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
It was still a long time ago.
The so-called currency promise - the condition for leaving for the West - was only given to "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czech currency was not a freely convertible currency, so without a currency guarantee it would have been impossible to raise the funds (Western currency) needed for a trip to the West.
So far most Czechs have spent their holidays inland, and it is no wonder that the Czechs have bought countless weekend homes and dacha - a habit that continues to this day.
The 1989 revolution was followed by a Czech travel revolution.
While until 1989 a holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria was the norm, the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their holidays abroad in countries around the world last year.
A huge paradox that is no longer well understood today is the fact that until 1989 one could not travel to the most popular holiday country of the Czech Republic - Croatia - because it was part of Yugoslavia.
As early as the 1990s, the foreign exchange requirement in neighbouring Western European countries was abolished, leading to a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna, Austria and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks simply could not get enough of their travels to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to be there for at least a few days.
The Czech holidaymakers who went to Paris slept in tents in the park, because who would have had the money to stay in a hotel or a boarding house?
A typical feature of Czech travel abroad at the time was a suitcase packed with cans, beer and sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely convertible Czech crown - after decades our tourists were finally able to freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living and thus our average wages increased, which marked another important moment in 1997.
The increased demand for travel led travel agencies to start regularly preparing charter flights after 1997, making flights incredibly cheaper than in the past, thanks to the possibility of negotiating discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the United States, had already made currency-free payments with all the highly developed countries of the world, making travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-assembly travel came in 2000, when the first direct charter flight to an exotic country was made to Thailand due to high demand.
Since then, direct charter flights with Czech passengers have taken place annually in remote sunny countries; this year, 12 exotic destinations are flown directly from the Czech Republic.
The 100 Tsd. Czechs travel to exotic countries every year!
Another important moment in the epoch that marked our "post-revolutionary" development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, making our country definitely one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, for the first time, Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, they spent more than CZK 15 per person for a single holiday including the cost at the resort.
