The most beautiful swimming pools in Europe
Jump to blue
By Julia Stanek
Planning pools in UFO optics, magnificent pools in Budapest: If you travel through Europe, you can experience your blue wonder - and after a city tour or a walk, your tired legs can rest in spruce baths.
A book shows where wellness in the water is most beautiful.
When Iris Meder went on a research trip over the past year and a half, one thing was not to be missing in her luggage: her swimsuit.
Leaning back on the water, she looked up into artfully designed domes, swimming to marble whores waiting for her at the edge of the basin, and marveling at carefully restored youth-style swimming pools.
If she liked a bath, she would take it in her notebook - along with some interesting details about the building's architecture and history.
More than 200 swimming pools were explored in this way by architectural historian Meder - and she now presents them in her new book "Badgefreuden": Folk Swimming Halls in Munich, historic bathing palaces in the Black Forest, "Hardcore-Beton Buildings" in the Taunus.
She travelled through 13 countries to visit the most extraordinary baths in Central Europe: Germany, Austria and Switzerland, as well as places in Italy, France, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland - and a city in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia.
The 46-year-old German is a true swimming culture enthusiast.
She doesn't have much of a mind for sport, says Meder - only in the water is it different.
The only thing annoying is that swimming fans have to get along with blue tiles and chlorine tanks while joggers can breathe the charming scent of fig forests or listen to the cheerful bird whistle in the park.
"I wondered one day why swimming pools always have to be so ugly", says the Vienna-based midwife.
"So I started collecting beautiful baths".
Water surface doubled architecture
The wellness factor in bathrooms is so great because all the senses are served, says Meder.
And when the builders have worked hard, swimming pools can be a real treat: "Instead of a foot floor, bathtubs have a water surface".
"It is transparent on the one hand, but reflects the beauty of the whole building on the other".
Everything doubles visually: high vaults, colorful tiles, jump boards.
The small-format "Badgefreuden" series of 190 pages provides information on the architectural and cultural history of historic wellness oases, but above all it is a blue leap.
Remarkable specimens were discovered by the pool collector Meder during her research in Hungary.
In addition to magnificent thermal baths, such as the 100-year-old Széchenyi Bath in Budapest, she found a nitrate-rich water in a pristine karst cave (a cave bath in Miskolc-Tapolca) and a thermal bath with pools filled with alkaline water and located in a bottle-shaped building (Városi Termálfürdö in Jászberény).
On the other hand, many heated open-air baths in Switzerland and Austria offer spectacular views: while you can see the whole city from the Zurich rooftop bath, you can look out at the snow-covered Arlberg in the outdoor pool of a bath in St. Anton - and: There is a window in the steam bath from which you can watch the ski slope.
Perhaps the most extraordinary pool design awaits bathers in Längenfeld: the Ötztal Aquadome looks like a UFO landing right in the Alps.
From three open shells it evaporates in winter, while in the background the mountains of the Ötztal reach the sky.
Alhambra in the Black Forest
Not every swimming pool was filled with chlorine.
Many thermal baths smell of sulfur, and the Árpád bath in Békescsaba, Hungary, smells of heating oil so bad that it's hard to believe it's landed in a health bath.
The smell comes from the alkaline, hydrogen-carbonated, almost black, healing water whose flavor sticks to your skin as soon as you slip into the pool - a wellness experience of a special kind.
However, Iris Meder was disappointed in her search for beautiful bathing spots at one place: When she wanted to visit the open-air and sunbathing area in the Czech city of Bad Luhatschowitz, she found a locked area.
The bath designed by architect Dušan Jurkovic in 1902 has since been closed.
As she glanced through the weathered windows of the red-white-yellow youth-style building, she saw weeds growing among the tiles.
The decay was countered by a magical swimming pool in the Black Forest, the Palais Thermal in Bad Wildbad.
Three phases of construction have already been completed; not only can you discover neo-Romanesque elements from the time of its construction in 1844, but you can also discover a Moorish hall in the Alhambra style, which was added around 1900.
Since its careful modernization in 1995, the Palais Thermal has been the favorite swimming pool of Iris Meder - not only because it originally came from the Black Forest.
"It's an achievement to merge so many different building styles into such a great unit", says Meder.
In such a palace, the plunge into the thermal pool is obviously a matter of convenience.
