21st house in Vienna
The moved pavilion
By Ingeborg Wiensowski
An architectural history with highs, lows and happy end: The Austrian World Exhibition Pavilion in Brussels in 1958 won awards, became a museum in Vienna, stood empty and camouflaged.
Now it's reopening as an exhibition hall.
If we are surrounded by modern postwar architecture, clear shapes, glass halls, bold swinging and new building materials, typical of the belief in technological progress, then the Austrian pavilion of the architect Karl Schwanzer for the 1958 Brussels World's Fair is a fitting and famous example.
Schwanz's Pavilion won the Grand Prix d'Architecture for its lightweight and floating steel-glass construction.
The building is still considered a milestone in contemporary architecture.
He made the architect so famous that he also built the Austrian Pavilion at the next world exhibition.
With its legendary BMW four-cylinder house plus a shot-like side-building in Munich, it finally became internationally famous in 1973.
Its pavilion, which was planned as a temporary exhibition building, was erected in the Swiss Garden near Vienna's South Station after the World's Fair, was renovated and in 1962 a 20th-century museum was opened there - the "20th House" was named.
The building was neither spatially nor technically suitable as a museum - no walls for hanging art, no good climate.
Nevertheless, it was used for so long that contemporary art in Vienna got a new home.
Since 2001, the building has been empty and has been falling more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has rebuilt the pavilion, now called "House of 21" and will be used in the future as a museum of contemporary art.
Tuesday night, the Belvedere Museum, which houses the house, opens its first exhibition - a lucky one in every way.
The new start was made by Agnes Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian Belvedere Gallery in 2007.
Husslein-Arco, a doctoral student in art history with a distinguished career as a young ice artist, later at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Museum of Modern Salzburg, continued to push for the conversion of politicians and monument patrons, obtaining public and private sponsorship funds and establishing the use.
In addition to contemporary art, the works of sculptor Fritz Wotruba from the same foundation were to be exhibited, there was to be a café and a bookstore, and an office building had to be built for this purpose.
Strict supervision and small budget
The ideal cast for the implementation was Krischanitz.
Not only because he had sensibly rebuilt and expanded Joseph Olbrich's Secession in Vienna and won the competition, but because he had studied at Schwanz at the Technical University of Vienna and the pavilion was an "unrememberedly important place" for him where he had been "looking at the exhibitions almost every weekend".
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which lost its generosity and lightness when it was moved to Vienna and reused.
The current renovation was a much bigger problem: the building was "an energy dump", says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass façade were replaced, glass fibre reinforced insulating glass was used and the glass roof was replaced by special safety glass.
Cold-bridge steel bearings have been reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled ceilings have been repaired.
Two basements made room for new use, a lowered light trench between the house and the street provides exposure, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the lightweight Swan Pavilion.
The original exterior doors remain, the house is painted in the old red-brown red-colored red-colored.
And the movie theater is still exactly the same as it was before.
And all this under strict supervision of the Monuments Authority and on a small budget.
"Often, a material had to be found that was good and cheap and also liked by the Monuments Protection Office", says Krischanitz, pointing to a rough floor in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and alterations, the building has remained flexible and light.
The pavilion "which came from Brussels" was difficult, Krischanitz recently said, a typical "drop-in-the-city story".
Such an architecture "always stands in the wrong place" and yet "wants to awaken a right awareness".
In this case, the 21st House is not in the wrong place, however, because it is an urban fortune: the entirely newly planned "Highway Headquarters" with office and residential buildings is being built around the Swiss garden.
And another lucky thing may come up: the 21st House could get reinforcement from another Krischanitz building, because the collector Francesca of Habsburg bought the Berlin temporary art gallery, and as you hear, she's already negotiating with the city for a neighboring location in the Swiss garden.
