Although Breivik may have acted alone, he is far from alone in cyberspace: he spent a lot of time in front of his computer until his attack and chatting with some of the millions of nationalists who support far-right groups on social media sites.
After the tragedy of this summer, researchers wanted to find out more about these people.
But how do you find them?
It's easy - you just have to log in to Facebook.
"We found it not difficult to reach them", says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recent report by the British think tank DEMOS on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook's concealment of personal data is so encyclopaedic, Bartlett says, that researchers simply have to use the site's advertising tool to pinpoint their desired demographic data with scientific accuracy - just like marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of far-right groups across Europe and then targeted them with ads, but instead of linking to a new band or diet product, the Adds users were asked to participate in a survey that asked about their educational status, their attitude toward violence, and their own assessment of their future.
Thanks to Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 followers of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - without even having to leave their office once.
"It's a fairly new research method", says Bartlett.
Some of the findings are hardly surprising, as online advocates of far-right groups are mostly young, male and angry about immigration.
But in a kind of surprising twist, "those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more rational, democratic, and less violent than those who sit behind their computer screens".
DEMO's work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a hot new tool in the hands of scientists.
Ideas makers, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to societal trends like likes, text messages and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding on average three pieces of content per day, Facebook's "Datensupernova" is generating a research boom that has led to an almost 800% increase in the number of scientific papers with this page's name in the title over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that you can study people through this site, which you don't normally reach with your clipboard on the street.
"When you tried to interview people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them".
"They had to inform the party first and they would never have been allowed in", says Bartlett.
"Facebook takes all that away - you go straight to them".
Others say the site offers a way to identify and solve social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues found that students who discussed their drunkenness on Facebook were significantly more likely to drink problematically than students who were silent about it.
Moreno suggests that peer students, like housing counselors, monitor the site and help a student if he posts too many status updates.
"You can't solve a problem if you haven't recognized it", said Dimitri Christakis, Moreno's co-author and director of Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children's Research Institute in Seattle, Washington Post.
"We have found a way to identify vulnerable children who would otherwise not have been found".
Facebook also constantly taps into the data of its own population.
The site's data team has compiled statistics on relationship status and Valentine's Day, voter turnout in the 2010 midterm elections, and a national happiness index (using primarily data that only Facebook has access to - masters of digital freedom have long known that the site should make its big data trench accessible to others for research purposes.)
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them whether they want to or not, and to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away, you allow the site to release your personal data.
But what if Facebook users become part of a survey they don't even know anything about yet?
While researchers have strict guidelines on how to collect their data offline, everything is allowed online.
"I don't think many users have thought about the fact that a researcher could study their profiles", says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, to a 2006 study examining the public pages of students on Facebook.
"As far as she was concerned, it was all about her and her friends".
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there's no guarantee that a research participant is absolutely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know how much of the information in a user profile and in posts is true.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things", Selwyn says.
So, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn still thinks that a clipboard and a pen are the best research tools anyone can use.
"There is no substitute for going out into the real world and talking to real people", he says.
