How much deception are we experiencing?
Studies show that we lie between 10 and 200 times a day.
But many of these lies are considered to be emergency lies.
Another study shows that strangers lie to each other three times during the first 10 minutes of a meeting.
To detect lies or to "discover lies" is something that is important for every person to learn, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from a social game, such as charades where the goal is to shout "Have you!" the instigation of a deception is a serious area of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities that have undertaken extensive research projects, particularly in the fields of psychology and physiology.
One result of the research is that most of the ancient myths about lying have been debunked.
Lies look you in the eye.
They don't always stutter, stutter, red and stabbed.
But this does not mean that these liars are difficult to detect and expose.
A trained liar can penetrate the truth by learning about the structure of the statement, the fine facial expressions, the question and timing.
I've spent several years researching the scientific findings of the ever-growing, comprehensive field of disguise, and it's clear that disguise is a modern skill that's easy to learn and helps us to navigate our complex world, especially when hiring or questioning people or negotiating or managing is part of our professional responsibilities.
Good liars are very good at judging other people, arousing their interest and controlling their own emotions. And they intuitively sense how they are perceived by others.
Research shows that extroverted people lie more often than introverted people, that men lie more often than women, whose lies are more "oriented" - usually to protect the feelings of others - that married people lie to their partners less often than unmarried people (but the lies they tell are usually "fat lies").
We also know that when a person is exposed as a criminal, others feel less guilty about lying to that person.
How do you tell if someone's lying?
First, by observing the normal behavior of that person.
This is called baselining, the starting position.
It provides a reference point for the subsequent evaluation of changes.
Observe the attitude, the laughter, the quality of the voice of the subject.
You should know better when someone is usually tripping all the time, so you don't blame him wrongly for tripping during a meeting.
Then watch for a buildup of noticeable verbal and nonverbal behaviors.
Consider these accumulations to be alarm bells ringing, not evidence of disembodied.
People who cheat may stutter when they try to remember their history, or they may point their feet toward the door or they may lean toward the exit, or they may significantly change their position or show a "relaxation after the interview", that deep, relaxing exhalation and the change in attitude when all the hard questions are over.
Askers often mistakenly signal that an interview is over just to look for that relaxation after the interview.
Also, be careful of the language of your subject.
Scott Peterson's slide is famous for using the past form, claiming that his murdered wife was still alive and sparking a national search for her.
Deceptive people can also use distant language, like, "I didn't have sex with this woman, Miss Lewinsky", or repeat a tricky question throughout.
The most common verbal signs are subtle.
Some people use "qualifying language" when answering a tricky question: "Well... to tell you the truth... as far as I know... from the best of my knowledge and conscience".
This makes the answer more perceptual than factual, often causing alarm bells to ring.
There is no magic to disguise lies, but you can learn skills that make disguise possible.
