The Prime Minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to introduce him to the new government which is to confront the crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic collapse.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, who was appointed on Sunday, would meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm the government formation.
It is expected that he will represent a majority cabinet of technocrats, although it is not yet clear when the new prime minister will take office.
Monti said he would present the results of the talks with the political parties on government formation to the President of the State.
"I want to reaffirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to cope with these difficult times", the former EU Commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly confirm the government formation, but his comments show that the obstacles have been overcome.
"The frame is now well-packed", he added.
Monti has managed to form a government in less than three days, which is much less than normal, while Italy is struggling with a political and financial crisis that has pushed the cost of debt to unbearable levels.
The new government, led by former EU Commissioner Monti, must adopt a tough austerity package demanded by European politicians to restore the shattered confidence in Italy.
The pressure on Monti to act quickly was further increased by the volatile market situation, which has led to a 7% interest rate on Italian government bonds for 10 years, which corresponds to the situation in which Greece and Ireland were forced to apply for the European bailout.
Emma Marcegaglia, president of the Confindustria Italian industrial association, told the press after a meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government with all our might".
We believe this government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this emergency.
Montis' chances of success were greatly increased by the support of Silvio Berlusconi's PDL party, which was forced to resign on Saturday as a result of the crisis.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are destined to bring good results", said Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party.
The support of the PDL, Italy's largest party, is essential because so far many of its members have spoken out against a majority technocratic government currently formed by Monti.
Parliament's support
The new Monti government needs strong parliamentary support to implement the probably unpopular austerity measures.
Resistance to its efforts or delaying reforms could lead to another devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks is also pressing, pointing out that a failure by Montis is a disaster.
Monti began his debates with political parties, trade unions and business associations, as well as youth and women's organisations, on Monday.
The round of hearings is scheduled to conclude on Tuesday evening.
Monti was appointed this Sunday by Napolitano, who has launched an extremely rapid change of government in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite towards the end of last week when it was announced that Berlusconi would step down, the costs of Italian government bonds have reached critical limits again as a result of uncertainty over the success of the new prime minister.
A bailout of Italy with a national debt of 1.8 trillion euros would be too much for the current EU bailout.
Monti said his government must wait until the next elections, which are expected to be held in 2013, despite predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement the reforms rather than prefer the elections.
