This was confirmed by the group's bassist and co-founder, Jeff Ament, who gave an exclusive interview last week from Brazil to Viva.
The band is on the South American leg of their 20th anniversary tour and on Sunday, the 20th, they'll make their only stop in Central America.
On that day, they will perform at the National Stadium from 7:30 p.m. with the band The X from Los Angeles and Las Robertas from Costa Rica.
You are reading an excerpt from the interview, a full copy of which can be found in the online edition of La Nación.
For your Costa Rican fans, a dream comes true when Pearl Jam plays in Costa Rica: Do you realize what that means for your fans?
Playing in Costa Rica is a dream come true for us too.
This is just the second time we've played in South and Central America, and so far it's been great.
I've only been to Costa Rica on vacation once, and it's such a beautiful country that we're sure to stay there for a few more days.
We're excited to bring our music there.
I'm asking you this because the band's fans are so dedicated, they're experiencing the days before the concert the most intensely.
What do you say to your most enthusiastic fans?
Thank you for being there for us all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica, and thank you for waiting so long, and we're sorry we took so long to get here.
Some people even think your concert will be the biggest show of the year.
Isn't that a little pressure from your visit?
Some of the greatest shows we've done in the last 21 years have been in the last two weeks.
We played a couple of giant shows in Sao Paulo and we hope they've made us fit for this concert in Costa Rica.
We really like playing there.
We love this country, we love surfing and we're fascinated by the jungle, which is why Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you meet Costa Rica and its surf waves?
Many of our friends are surfers, and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo, where the waves are just unimaginable.
My friends have always gone to Costa Rica and Nicaragua to surf, and together with Mexico, these are great surfing places, and that's how we learned about surfing-loving people.
You guys have been doing a lot of gigs on the tour.
What are your plans for the event in Costa Rica?
Since we've never played there before, we're not setting boundaries.
We're going to try to put on the best show possible with a lot of different songs, and we want to play a few songs from each album and give our fans a good, versatile repertoire.
You never repeat your repertoire.
Why? Why?
I think part of the reason is that we have nine records and we can play over 120 songs, and everyone likes a different song, so it's not easy to decide which one we're going to play.
If we put two or three songs in the repertoire that we haven't played in a while, we can better maintain our concentration and they surprise us because they remind us of the reasons why we liked those songs. Otherwise, they could get forgotten.
That makes the show more interesting for us and I think that's why the audience is interested.
This tour is to celebrate your 20th anniversary.
Looking back, do you find it hard to believe your success?
Yes, I totally did.
First of all, I don't think any of us ever imagined playing in a great rock band for over 20 years.
We continue to put our trust in that blessing and find it wonderful to be able to make music together even now.
We like each other and are excited to produce music.
We're lucky to be able to travel to places in the world we've always wanted to visit.
Things couldn't have been any better.
What did it mean to you to have been an active participant in the Grunge's birthday party?
It's always been an honor to be part of this group of great bands.
We're good friends with the people from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising and quite unusual when a movement arises from a group of friends.
Occasionally, a band comes out of a city, but it's unusual for five or ten groups to come out of the same city at the same time.
We're proud of it and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
Sometimes we still play together.
Last year, we went to a festival with Alice in Chains and in Canada with Mudhoney and we saw Soundgards on their tour, and we're excited to still be friends with them all, and we're honored to be part of this Seattle sound that's been coming up.
It's also very unusual for a band like yours to have stayed with the same musicians for so long.
Yeah, four of us have been playing together for 21 years, and Matt (Cameron) came to us 13 years ago, which alone is way more time than many bands have survived.
First of all, I think we all feel lucky to be alive and we care about each other.
We're all close friends, which is why we've opened up musical avenues that give everyone the freedom to experiment.
We're confident in each other and their music.
Your relationship with fame has not always been easy, but on the other hand, thanks to your success, you could always do what you wanted.
How do you find balance?
The way we've grown up has made it easier for us to find balance.
We're making sure we don't go on tour too often, because it's too easy to get caught up in this game with huge crowds of people who love your music.
As long as you remember that people came here for music, it reminds you that you have to pay attention to music and what it created, without being obsessed with being a famous rock star.
What are your memories of your other project, Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote some really good songs and it was great at first.
We were a band for three years that had never released an album until Andy's death.
We were disappointed that we needed so much time, and we're still good friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who formed the band with us. When I hear a song or see photos, I think about what an incredible person Andy was and how he made me laugh.
He was an extraordinary person, and we miss him.
The local band Las Robertas is responsible for opening the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know her work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose the band for the opening?
Yeah, the production sent us videos from several bands and we liked this band the best, so we're curious to see what Las Robertas has to offer live.
Why do you always change the lyrics of Yellow Ledbetter when you play live?
This is a question for Ed, I have no idea.
He sings it, and I think he sings the first thing he thinks of.
Who influenced you as a bass player?
Of so many+
The first people I think of are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There's so many of them I could talk about the bassists I like all afternoon.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the Grunge alive when it's no longer a fashion phenomenon?
I don't think we're all too attached to the word grunge.
When I think about it, I think about the bands I mentioned earlier, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and everyone else who came up at the same time, and if they're still relevant today, I think that's great because it's worth listening to that music, and bands like Mudhoney are making better music than ever.
At first her music was darker, now she's more positive.
Why? Why?
That's interesting, because I think there are a few songs on the new album that might seem a little lighthearted, but there are also other songs like The End or Just Breathe that are classified as very dark songs, even though they have something positive in them.
I was crying when I heard Ed play them.
I think when you get older and something traumatic happens in your life -- for example, when you lose a family member or a friend -- it affects your artistic creation and your music and these two songs clearly embody that for me.
But I also think you can be a happy person and still make dark music.
