MSS announces a research protocol to find the gene for obesity
The Social Security Institute of Mexico is leading a research project to find the gene for obesity in children and adolescents, supported by specialists from the IPN.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social - IMSS (Institute of Social Security of Mexico) announced that it is leading a research project to discover the gene for obesity in children and adolescents entitled 'Genetics of childhood and adolescence obesity' to identify the genetic markers associated with obesity.
Miguel Cruz López, Head of the Unidad de Investigación Médica en Bioquímica (Department of Medical Research, focusing on Biochemistry) at the Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, explained that an interdisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been set up.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students at the Instituto Nacional de Salud Pública (INSP) and the Centro de Investigación y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinvestav) of the Instituto Politécnico Nacional (IPN).
The public is invited to participate in the study, and interested parties can come to the IMSS sports fields in the Valley of Mexico, where tests are conducted with children and adolescents every Saturday from 8.00 a.m.
He stressed that the investigation had begun at the Cuauhtémoc Sports Centre (in the west of the State of Mexico) and has been continuing since 8 October at the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Centre (in the east of the State of Mexico).
If the target of 500 to 600 researchers is reached, the study will continue at the Sports Square in Independencia (south of the capital district) and will be completed at the Morelos Stadium (north of the capital district).
He explained that the aim of the study was to identify the factors and role of genetics in the development of obesity and identify risk factors in Mexican children and adolescents for the prevention of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of World Diabetes Day, he said that the aim was to have 3,000 children and adolescents aged six to 14 years old fill out nutrition questionnaires with the consent and supervision of their parents.
They will also be asked questions about their physical activity and family history of illness to help control risk factors that could lead to diabetes or kidney failure.
It further stated that on those Saturdays, the subjects were measured (weight, size, waist circumference), their blood pressure was monitored and blood levels such as glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic factors (an attempt to identify genes related to childhood obesity) were determined.
Cruz López stressed that this study would be carried out in the wake of healthcare workers' concerns about the alarming weight gain of young people.
"The health surveys conducted in 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years the proportion of obese boys increased by 77 percent and that of obese girls by 47 percent, and that overweight also increased dramatically", stressed the IMSS specialist.
He said the search for genetic markers was justified because the genetic history of the population of Mexico was different from that of other peoples.
He stated that an average Mexican is 65 percent Native American, 30 percent European, and 5 percent African, reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and obesity.
He explained that the genetics of obesity are expressed in the inability to burn the excess energy (calories) we take in, so that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit to the study participants was a comprehensive examination of the children to determine whether they were overweight or obese.
It would even investigate the presence of dark skin folds in the neck and forearm (acanthosis), which indicate the likelihood of metabolic disorders and pre-stage diabetes.
All information would be kept confidential and the doctors would notify the parents in writing, explaining to the parents all the results of the tests and suggesting lifestyle changes appropriate to preventing illness.
Cruz López explained that there are three basic factors responsible for overweight, obesity, and other chronic diseases: lack of movement, meaning lack of exercise in everyday life, spending most of the day watching television, and using transportation instead of walking short distances.
The high calorie intake, i.e. increased consumption of sugary drinks and carbohydrates (tamask, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) together with high fat and protein intake, and the genetics to be analysed in this research project.
Asphalt from UNAM prevents holes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the University of Mexico, UNAM, develops polymer-modified asphalt to make the mixture more resistant to weather and temperature fluctuations
If the signs from the road surface were taken into account, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200 000 pits if the rainy season broke out in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México, said Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at UNAM University, warning that if the laying and maintenance of the asphalt surface were adequate, the number of pits would be significantly reduced or even completely avoided.
In his talk "Technical Holes", which he gave on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory he was responsible for would develop polymer-modified asphalt to produce a mixture similar to asphalt but with greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera argued that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behaviour of road pavement and thus prevent the occurrence of pits.
He explained that asphalt - the heaviest part of petroleum - is a hydrocarbon compound, one part of which has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphaltene - and the other part a low - the so-called malthene. Together they give the road surface its characteristic tethelist behaviour.
The asphalt's counting behaviour means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180°C, at 120°C it is very fluid and at 50°C it is almost solid, while at very low temperatures it becomes brittle.
"This means that the resistance of asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes over the course of a day depending on weather conditions and temperature fluctuations", the chemical engineer explained.
The researcher from FQ noted that the streets of Mexico City had a mostly flexible road surface, consisting of six layers of material, the last three of which included asphalt.
Between the top layers is a layer of asphalt, made of small, asphalt-washed stones that are then solidified.
Every single piece of this wear layer was bathed in asphalt.
If the vehicles move on it and forces are generated, this layer allows for a good distribution of forces in the road surface.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would be even better distributed", said the chemical engineer.
"On top of the wear sheet", he explained, "a final layer is laid out, the so-called bearing layer, made of tiny stones, that is, sand, which has also been bathed in asphalt.
Since these layers are in contact with the vehicle tyres, they require a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and must cause friction.
The most powerful and distributing of these road surfaces is the bearing layer which also requires a suitable thickness and the material from which it is made must be maintained.
Climate conditions, particularly humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to consider, above all water", he said, "because they significantly affect the behaviour of the wear layer.
When the terrain becomes wet, water enters the layer and is difficult to get out of it again, causing all the layers of the road surface to soften and, as a result, to form holes.
If a hole occurs", he said, "the cover is first removed, while the wear layer is only affected afterwards. But the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that should be maintained at the first signs by appropriate maintenance programs".
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (National Research System of Mexico) explained that vehicle loads are another important cause of the occurrence of crashes, so the thickness of each layer of the road surface should always be proportional to the vehicle load and that this should be ensured to avoid frequent crashes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there was still a lot of research to be done, for example on asphalt emulsions, which are already on the market in other countries and can be used to repair the holes easily and without applying high temperatures.
