This was the work of the doctor who identified Alfonso Cano's body.
A Lophoscopist from Cali went down in history as the man who identified "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials plays a key role.
On November 4, a Lophoscopist from the Investigative Unit of the Public Prosecutor's Office (CTI) from Cali came in as the man who confirmed the identity of the leader of the FARC (Fuerzas Armadas Revolucionarias de Colombia - Revolutionary Forces of Colombia) by comparing the fingerprints.
Of the seven lophoscopists in the CTI department, this week Eliazar González was on duty, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been involved in criminal investigations for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in communities in Chocó, where he often had to travel for five days in the jungle to reach the location of the bodies he was to identify.
In 2000, he moved to Valle and after completing the required courses, he specialized in lophoscopy, which is the examination of the skin exposed to friction, i.e. the palms of the hands and feet.
During the week of the operation against the so-called Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was instructed to pack clothes for at least three days.
Something big was coming.
On Friday night, he flew from Palmira to Cauca by helicopter.
He knew he had to identify two bodies, and that there was a suspicion that one might be that of the man who led the world's oldest guerrilla, so he had to take the fingerprint sheet of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
However, when he examined the body and reached the site, he could not identify it because of its physical appearance, which was not in the least similar to the images he had seen in the mass media.
He had no beard, was dressed like a local farmer, wore no glasses, and was much thinner.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Armed with a magnifying glass, ink, a plant cell, and a flashlight, Eleazar compared the body's fingerprints to those on the printing plate.
He saw it right, it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, this man from Puerto Tejada was responsible for telling Defense Minister Juan Carlos Pinzón that it was actually the head of the FARC.
Searching for traces
For a Sijín datyloscope in Cali, the award given by President Juan Manuel Santos Eliazar González at a press conference on the use of "Cano" was very important.
A lot of people don't know what we do.
Daktyloscopy is an exact science with no error rate, which can be a key factor in solving a crime.
