Austria
The introduction of a 'Golden Rule' into the Constitution
The government of the Greater Social Democratic/Christian Democratic Coalition, which is in power in Austria, decided on Tuesday to incorporate a "Golden Budget Rule" into the constitution in order to reduce public deficits and also to avoid any degradation by rating agencies in Austria's top credit rating (AAA).
It was the Social Democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann who announced this decision in person, although the Austrian public debt is 74.6%, well above the criterion of 60% set by the Maastricht Treaty, but well below the debt levels of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
"If Austria's solvency had not fallen from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay an additional three billion euros of interest every year", argued Michael Spindelegger, Vice Chancellor and Christian Democratic Minister of Foreign Affairs.
Austria is also holding a call at the Brussels Eurozone Summit on 26 October: the Heads of State or Government had demanded that the reduction of public deficits be included in the Constitution by the end of 2012 and that the public account balance be returned to the public account by the adoption of an equivalent law.
The Austrian government's approach to this is similar to the German model, as Germany was the first European country to incorporate such a rule into the constitution.
The structural budget deficit should decrease by 0,75% of GDP each year by 2017, and from 2017 onwards the structural budget deficit of the Federal State should not exceed the 0,35% threshold of GDP, while regional states and municipalities should have balanced budgets.
The objective is to eliminate budgetary liabilities below the 60% criterion laid down in the Maastricht Agreement by 2020/21.
