If there is a subject that cannot be dealt with on the basis of short-term considerations or emotions, it is certainly energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affect the purchasing power and competitiveness of enterprises.
It is reasonable to hold an election to consider this issue and the position of nuclear energy.
The debate will only bear fruit if it examines the overall economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French should base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
Although there are 7 billion people on this planet, demographic evolution is driving a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, so a huge proportion of the world's population doesn't have to forfeit a vital element.
At the same time, the scarcity of fossil resources must be mitigated in order to continue to produce electricity sustainably, without forgetting the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, a theme that has disappeared from the ecological debate, in order to combat climate irregularities.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
Germany therefore remains isolated in its decision to forgo nuclear power.
This is not the case in Belgium, which has decided to find a substitutable source, or in Switzerland, which is planning to build only last generation nuclear power plants.
The United Kingdom, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name but a few, continue to pursue their projects with determination.
The United States, for its part, has decided to add another unit to its park after Fukushima by reopening the Three Mile Island plant, which was shut down after the nuclear accident.
The German model of renewable energy is sometimes cited as a model, but the reality is contrary to the discourse.
The Berlin election will take the form of a rise in electricity prices, an increase in energy dependence on imported gas, especially Russia, and an increase in CO2 emissions from gas and coal plants.
The full extent of these unpleasant effects will be apparent within a few months.
The case of Denmark gives us reason to think.
Denmark is the European leader in wind energy, which generates 30% of its electricity, and one of the largest users of coal and gas, which are used alternately with wind energy, resulting in a 65% and 50% increase in CO2 emissions and electricity prices respectively.
The Commission has already decided to take the necessary measures to ensure that the Community's energy policy is consistent.
In the global economy, energy prices are a key factor in competitiveness and in the stability of industry at national level, and French companies have an advantage because of the cheapest electricity in Europe.
Any significant reduction in nuclear power would therefore lead to a sharp increase in energy prices, which would make the noble statements about the reindustrialisation of our country and the defense of purchasing power an illusion.
Polls showed that this is a price that the vast majority of French people are not willing to pay, as well as resistance to the principle of this source of energy.
Let us now consider that the energy policy of our country has made it possible to create an industry with 125.00 direct and 410,000 induced jobs.
The Commission has also proposed a number of measures to improve the quality of the products and services provided by the Member States.
If France decides to leave nuclear power, a large part of these SMEs will be affected and the annual export of investment goods and nuclear energy of EUR 6 billion will shrink further and further.
What electrician would hire an EPR designed to run for sixty years if the decline of its producer is preprogrammed?
To solve the energy equation, we must admit that there is no miracle tool for generating electricity, just as there is no devil's work.
The low-carbon solutions developed by Areva for the use of nuclear and renewable energy are evidence of the complementarity of energy sources.
The maintenance of the highest possible level of safety is an absolute imperative for nuclear power.
In France we have a security authority that has carried out uncompromising and transparent checks on existing works, such as the construction in Flamanville.
Their working teams, which have made a name for themselves because of their professionalism, are obsessed with the concept of safety.
In the last 50 years, the nuclear industry has seen three major disruptions.
Only one, Three Mile Island, has been operated under normal conditions, with no human or environmental consequences.
In Chernobyl, the drama was evoked by reactor construction and endless human failure.
In Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was caused by two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude, which killed tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident as it did from the two preceding ones.
The EPR is a project which, as a result of this approach and the cooperation of the safety authorities of the French and German operators and constructors of nuclear power plants, enables it to be resilient to such phenomena.
As electrical engineers consider it desirable to build a nuclear power plant, a halt in Flamanville would be a fabulous gift to the competition of Areva and EDF, giving them the freedom to take the lead in the inevitable development of nuclear power.
It is inevitable and legitimate to seek the best energy bouquet for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotions, dogmas and party leaders dominate a debate that determines the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
