But this policy has rarely been analyzed from an economic point of view.
The Commission has already adopted a number of proposals for a directive on the protection of workers' rights.
On the right, the tone was set by Jacques Chirac, who declared in 1976 that '900,000 unemployed, including over 2 million immigrant workers, should not be a problem for a country', and on the left by Michel Rocard, who had stated in 1990 that France 'could not take in all the poverty in the world'.
The only difference is the degree of grossness
In 2005, the fear of the invasion of the national soil by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared by both the right and the left.
Both camps saw immigrants as a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of cruelty one is willing to admit to the immigrant.
Francois Hollande's programme is limited to banalities which suggest that partnership development will enable us to solve our 'migration problems'.
This idea of immigration as a burden, as a problem, may have an impact on the elections, but it is economically costly.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron present in a recent paper summarizing the latest findings on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 p.), there is broad consensus among experts on the positive impact of immigrant influences on economic growth, wages and jobs in immigrant countries.
The Commission has already decided to take a decision on the basis of the information available to it.
The fears about the influence of migrants are based on the idea that they threaten to replace local workers, especially the less skilled, by putting pressure on their wages.
Experience shows, however, that immigrants are in fact much more complementary than local wage workers, as they focus on occupations in sectors that are technically uncomfortable.
The low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that attract little local wage labourers, the more skilled among immigrants work in dynamic sectors where training is not matched by the job offer.
Positive wage effect
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country where there is a shortage of anesthesiologists, this complementarity between locals and migrants also has a positive effect on wages and the domestic labour market situation.
Giovanni Peri calculated that an increase of 1% in the influx of immigrants would lead to a corresponding long-term increase in real wages between 0.6% and 0.9%.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity of ideas introduced by immigrants is beneficial for creation and economic growth (high proportion of American-born immigrants among Nobel laureates; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants also contribute net to social systems, in European countries on average about 1% of total budgets.
For example, the World Labour Organization estimates that a 30-year-old immigrant to Germany makes a net contribution to the public budget (income minus expenditure) of around 150,000 euros on average over his lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to bring the missing intersections "with his teeth" to completion by the time he took office.
