Moleskine, a branded notebook.
Moleskine, founded by an Italian company about fifteen years ago, wants to give writing a new style.
It's got a flair for adventure, candlelight hours with writing.
Moleskine's notebook is easily recognizable, with its black, rectangular bookbinding, rubber band, eggshell pages, as it has aged over time.
However, the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was created in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a distinguished design notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then the company's technical advisor, is responsible for the launch of the new product.
The notebook was inspired by an old production technique called mole skin, which refers to a cotton wool, for example, used for upholstery benches.
This type of notebook was in great demand among writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has revived an old and almost forgotten object that was considered an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century", explains Maria Sebregondi, now brand manager at Modo Modo.
Success is coming.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% and established themselves with sales of 12,7 million units.
This is far from the usual production of the first years, when only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine crosses the Italian border and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to create a ghost image of the buyers, as the notebook enthralls business people as well as students and professionals.
Moleskine has the image of cosmopolitan, cultured and open-minded customers.
The small Italian company, which started with 12 employees, now employs over 100 people and has two offices since 2008; one in Milan and the other in New York.
The company sells its notebooks in bookstores, on internet portals such as Fnac, in small boutiques in the city centres and is committed to enforcing its identity.
"We have followed the spirit of the times and their new need for writing, which continues to exist despite the surge in e-mails", explained Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural feature is accompanied by the development of the company Moleskine: recently the brand has launched an exhibition called "Detour (Umweg) ", in which architects and artists exhibit their own notebooks.
In August, the company also launched a leopard-shaped booklet at the Locarno Film Festival.
Moleskine benefited from its success and this cultural spirit of the times and knew how to diversify its products: bags, calendar, filler, computer case... the brand has the full range of items.
A success that puts the borrower on the line: In the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, opening a new chapter in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers so high?
About 19% of disabled people are looking for work.
Today is the 15th Week of Work for the Disabled.
Despite a targeted public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate for disabled people is always twice the average: 19% versus 9% of the total population.
Discouraging?
"No", emphasizes Éric Blanchet, Director-General of the Adapt Association, which organizes the "Working Week for the Disabled".
"The progress made in 15 years is considerable".
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice as high, but three times as high".
"Nevertheless, there is still a tremendous amount of work to be done".
However, it must be said that many obstacles remain for the disabled unemployed to get a job.
The elderly are more likely to experience this: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% of them do not have a bachelor's degree and there are only 10,000 disabled students among the 2.3 million students with higher education degrees.
Finally, longterm unemployment is also very widespread: 53% of people with disabilities compared to 38% overall.
In short, there are so many criteria that make it difficult to return to work and that are at the heart of the problem, says Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association founded in 1992 that helps companies recruit disabled workers.
So much for the actual brakes.
The unspoken remains, the attitudes that are certain to develop but slow to develop.
A study conducted by the IMS Entrepreneurs' Association in April for the journal La Cité indicated that managers surveyed had "a low level of knowledge about disabled people" that was "overrepresented" by "people in wheelchairs, mentally or intellectually disadvantaged".
The result is that private companies with more than 20 employees still have a long way to go to achieve the target of 6% of disabled workers set by a 1987 law.
These figures, which date from 2008, represent a ratio of 2,6%.
"We are now at 3%", reports Pierre Blanc, director general of Agefiph, the organisation tasked with recruiting contributions from companies that violate this law.
The evidence: the number of 'fee paying' establishments decreased, as did the sum of the amounts paid between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which provides for contributions to be increased, put a strong pressure on companies", explained Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects real knowledge, particularly among the large groups of companies".
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of the establishments employing between 20 and 49 employees are handicapped workers, compared with 82% of enterprises employing between 100 and 199 employees.
